 Inorganic Couple: occupation cave painters - began as 2 completely separate objects initiated at different times for different reasons about a year apart. Often stone or metal and glass long to be together from the outset, but not here. It&apos;s as if these 2 objects grew up on other sides of an aesthetic country. 

They did in a way because at the time, the glass cold working studio was in a separate building from the main studio where all the other work was done. It was then moved into the main studio. A couple of months later the 2 of them met by accident when the roughed out glass piece was left on the metal machining bench next to a mostly uncarved block of aluminum. One of those storybook things- everyone knew they were meant for each other. She turned radiant in all her cut, optical crystal glory while remaining stolid, still, and mostly uncarved, he shone - transfixed by her sparkling glow. 

This is the kind of thing to look for since you found out in 1980 that sketching things out 1st just gets in the way. The dialogue begins with blocks, material, lumps- whatever. Then the process to get at their uncarved natures starts by filling a studio with as many promising starts as possible. Let them sort out what happens next. It may happen in a flash or a stubborn object can stand silent for years waiting for understanding. One piece may know what another needs and so on.

So everyday new conversations start and old ones continue. But none end. Finally, when it&apos;s clear a work is done, it can still take time before it explains itself. Or it&apos;s unnecessary. But when it is, they may never tell just because of that. 

Inorganic Couple wasn&apos;t at all shy or in any way reserved about who they are and what they do. Who&apos;d know better where cave painting would be if not for carbon and ocher? No where.

Inorganic is as inorganic does, carved or not.  
