New York Times T Magazine Sept. &apos;18 Design &amp; Luxury Issue -takeaways seem to go well with the overall WTF thing going on. Rather than go page by page just doing the letter from the editor- <b><a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/19/t-magazine/ts-design-luxury-issue-no-room-for-compromise.html?rref=collection%2Fissuecollection%2Fts-sept-23-design-luxury-issue&amp;action=click&amp;contentCollection=t-magazine&amp;region=rank&amp;module=package&amp;version=highlights&amp;contentPlacement=9&amp;pgtype=collection'>No Room for Compromise</a></b> by Hanya Yanagihara.

The title is of course apropos and kicks off with the pronoun &apos;I&apos; being used 7 times in the 1st paragraph of 4 sentences. Takeaway 1- we should always pay close attention to what a fascinating person&apos;s thinking about sharing next.  

The share is Takeaway 2- befriending someone in order to get praise from them is disappointing unless it&apos;s hard to do. In other words, it&apos;s about the chase- not the kill. And design/interiors directors are supposed to be tough to run down. 

This segued into Takeaway 3- when faced with flat rejection of your opinion with no attempt to find common ground you should be offended and have expected it all along because attempts to be accommodating are inherently dishonest.   

The rest of the Takeaways are better summed up in the editor&apos;s own (edited) words-

4- &quot;...(it&apos;s good to be) accommodating while also quietly, insistently, undeniably (unaccommodating)&quot; 

5- &quot;...most people to whom aesthetics deeply matter, ... (are) able to distinguish a compelling space from a space... (they can) actually enjoy inhabiting...&quot; 

6- &quot;A memorable interior, like any memorable piece of art, isn’t the one that’s likable but the one that evokes a strong reaction&quot;

7- &quot;...what’s the point of being nice?&quot; (apparently rhetorical, but unclear if being nice just has zero value or can actually be a negative) 

8- &quot;Anything really worth (experiencing) is something that at least some people will hate.&quot; (expansion on 6-)

9- &quot;The houses in this issue aren’t meant to appeal to everyone; they were meant to appeal to their owners, and that is why they appealed to us as well.&quot;

The last one&apos;s a little difficult to parse, but may mean something like-
