in glass annealing, the glass is carefully cooled very slowly to remove all the stress possible from the glass. this is done by letting glass come to uniform temperature just at the stress-relief point or &quot;strain point&quot; of the glass. for most kinds of glass, this strain point temperature is in the range of 454–482 °C (850–900 °F). below this point, any stress in the glass in trapped within the glass. if the remaining stress is too much, the glass will break as it continues to cool or days, months, or years later. 

glass is an excellent insulator- only transferring external temperature throughout it very slowly. in other words- when cooling- the outside of glass cools much faster than the inside making the surface shrink at a different rate than the inside or core thus causing stress trapped as it cools below the strain point because the glass is too hard move anymore while the center is still shrinking.

@vinkonings yes glass kilns are much the same as pottery kilns except they don&apos;t need to exceed 2000F. most pottery kilns need to run hotter for high-fire clays like porcelain and stoneware.

also, there&apos;s a big difference between water and glass because glass does not have a solid state. it is actually neither a liquid nor a solid- it is rather, an &quot;amorphous solid&quot; (when it seems solid it still has the molecular structure of a liquid like water. 

here&apos;s a <a href='https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/fact-fiction-glass-liquid/#:~:text=Glass%2C%20however%2C%20is%20actually%20neither,for%20changes%20to%20be%20visible.'>link that gives an in depth explanation</a>.

